## Part 7 — How All 4 Services Relate

The 4 services are **independent** but **logically connected** through data. Here's a real business scenario showing how they all work together:

```
REAL SCENARIO: Admin adds a new product and stocks it

STEP 1 — Create the item in Item Service
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
POST http://localhost:8081/api/items
{
  "name": "Wireless Mouse",
  "category": "Electronics"
}
Response: { "id": 1, "name": "Wireless Mouse" }

item_db → items table now has id=1


STEP 2 — Add stock in Inventory Service
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
POST http://localhost:8082/api/inventory
{
  "itemId": 1,          ← same id from step 1
  "quantity": 150,
  "warehouseLocation": "A1-North"
}

inventory_db → inventory table now tracks item 1


STEP 3 — Stock drops low, send notification
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
POST http://localhost:8083/api/notifications
{
  "eventType": "LowStock",
  "recipient": "manager@company.com",
  "message": "Stock for item 1 has dropped below threshold"
}

notification_db → notification logged


STEP 4 — Record everything in Audit Service
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
POST http://localhost:8084/api/audit-logs
{
  "serviceName": "Inventory Service",
  "operation": "UPDATE",
  "recordId": 1,
  "details": "Stock updated for item 1"
}

audit_db → audit log recorded
```

